Truthiness in Python

Python treats certain values as False in boolean context — these are called falsy.

# Falsy values
bool(0)        # False
bool(0.0)      # False
bool('')       # False — empty string
bool([])       # False — empty list
bool({})       # False — empty dict
bool(None)     # False

Everything else is truthy (non-zero numbers, non-empty containers, objects).

# Pythonic checks
if not items:        # ✓ check for empty list
if items == []:      # ✗ avoid — creates a new list
if x is None:        # ✓ identity check
if x == None:        # ✗ avoid — uses __eq__
if 0 < x < 100:     # ✓ chained comparison

Pitfall: mutable default arguments interact badly with truthiness checks.

Branching & Looping

if / elif / else — choose a path based on conditions:

score = 78
if score >= 90:
    grade = 'A'
elif score >= 75:
    grade = 'B'
else:
     grade = 'F'

for — iterate over any sequence (range, list, dict, …):

for i, name in enumerate(['Alice', 'Bob']):
    print(i, name)     # 0 Alice, 1 Bob

while — repeat until a condition changes; use break / continue for control:

while True:
    val = input('Enter a positive number: ')
    if val == "stop":
        break
    elif not val.isdigit():
        print("only int allowed")
    else:
        print(f"you entered {val}")

List Comprehensions — From Loop to One-liner

PatternTraditional for-loopList comprehension
Basic transformsquares = [] for x in range(10): squares.append(x**2)squares = [x**2 for x in range(10)]
With filterevens = [] for x in range(20): if x % 2 == 0: evens.append(x)evens = [x for x in range(20) if x % 2 == 0]
Nested (⚠ O(n²))pairs = [] for x in range(3): for y in range(3): pairs.append((x,y))pairs = [(x,y) for x in range(3) for y in range(3)]

Preamble: Why Does Complexity Matter?

  • Every algorithm consumes resources: time and memory
  • As input grows, poorly scaling code hits real-world limits
  • A brute-force solution may work for 100 items but crash at 1,000,000
  • Big O notation — O(…) — describes how resource usage grows with input size n
  • Two key dimensions:
  • Time complexity — how many steps / operations
  • Space complexity — how much memory is used
  • Goal: pick algorithms that scale well for the problem at hand
  • We will formalise this in Seminar 6 — this is your primer

Why Big O Matters

At n = 5000 the nested loop takes 0.9 s while the single loop finishes in 0.0002 s — that is a 4500× difference, and it only gets worse as n grows.

9 / 11

Key Takeaways

  • Python's truthiness: use if not items, if x is None
  • if / for / while cover all control flow you need
  • Prefer enumerate() over range(len(...))
  • Big O tells you how code scales — O(n) vs O(n²) matters
  • List comprehensions are faster and more readable than loops
  • Always think: how many times does this loop run?
